text: The task of accurately portraying DID in a movie is rare as all hell. Sybil was the best film, and handled the task very carefully, and well. This film, I have my doubts.  As someone with a split personality - possibly having DID as well. I must say that this task at hand is delicate. M. Night has previously shown himself to not be delicate. As Michael Bay demonstrated his storytelling with the shit-heap that was Pearl Harbor - I indeed hope this film will not become such a statistic.   I am willing to drop to my knees and beg for a good film. My biggest fear, being that this film is shit - but becomes the basis for what average people see DID as. I do not want to become an M. Night Shyamalan statistic. The title of this film alone made me weary. SPLIT? Really? As well as the idea that, "...it is believed that some can also manifest unique physical attributes for each personality." Is retarded - and it immediately drew me to the conclusion that M. Night did not do his homework.    Please - please be at least half decent. Otherwise, I expect a funny YMS review.

text: I'm a fan of M. Night Shyamalan, but he has some serious missteps in his career. I still have hope when I hear another movie of his coming out. I never saw sixth sense (odd i know), but I'll take everyone's word for it that it was good. I loved unbreakable, Signs, the Village (although not a fan of the "twist") and his recent outing, The Visit. The only ones I've seen that I didn't like were Lady in the Water and The Happening. I never had any desire to see The Last Airbender,  but I'll assume it's as bad as everyone says, and technically he really didn't have much to do After Earth except direct it. Apparently the script, story, editing, and such was pretty much left to Will Smith's "vision" so I don't think it's fair to blame him for that one. His quality is inconsistent, but I really really enjoyed The Visit, so hopefully he's learned his lesson and has paid attention to what the audience likes and dislikes and is on the right track again :)

text: Another movie about a (sometimes) transgender mentally ill serial killer? I don't have Dissociative Identity Disorder or MPD, but I have a dissociative disorder and I have a hard enough time getting my shit together to pay the bills and interact with the rest of humanity, without spending my spare time getting my kidnapping gear organized and tailing people.  People with visible mental illnesses are quite often the target of violence, and are systematically denied access to housing, employment and social stability, which marginalizes us to the point of commiting crime for the sake of survival.  Also, look up trans-antagonism sometime. Making one of his identities transgender is so played out it would be boring if it didn't contribute to violence against trans people.

text: I have a theory that Shamal...M Nights career is on a constant sloping scale of quality, kind of like William Butler Yeats' theory of the widening gyres. He started with his most critically acclaimed and popular movie, and they slowly decreased in quality until rock bottom (Last Air Bender/The Happening, take your pick). After Earth was bad, but it was still a movie, and then The Visit managed to even be good, so maybe this will begin to reach the level of quality of M Nights early career until he starts making better and better films. Maybe his last film will be as good as the Sixth Sense, completing the loop.

text: I'm not all that sure that I like the idea of this movie. Not because of the people directing it, or anything, but, because it gives such a misinformed view of what dissociative identity disorder (/formerly/ known as multiple personality disorder) really is. Why are people with DID always represented as being the crazy, insane, murderous psychopaths? People with DID are far more likely to hurt themselves than anyone else around them. Movies like this only continue to reinforce the stigma that people with DID are murderers. I'd love to see a movie with an accurate portrayal of DID, not the murderous, stigmatising stereotype that's been done to death already.

text: Perhaps I'm simply too sensitive to the matter, but with there already being blatant falsities about DID (Dissociative Identity Disorder), I really can't put much faith into this movie. The premise does have some promise, but the outcome is much too dependant on how certain details are handled. I personally believe that making yet another movie containing an antagonist with a mental disorder as severe (a different word has eluded me) as DID is likely to perpetuate stigma and fear. I'm assuming that there will be supernatural elements thrown in, but adding a diagnosis complicates matters.   There are plenty of mental disorders that have received unrealistic portrayals, both positive and negative, and I'm sure that Schizophrenia and PTSD immediately come to mind for many. For those of you planning to see this movie, it might be beneficial for you to read up on DID so that you can walk into the show with a bit more insight.   With all that being said, please have a lovely day/night. üòä

text: This is not as far fetched as people might think. There are cases of multiple personality disorder in which one personality is left handed and the other right handed, or one personality is near sided and the other far sided. This is shown in brain scans as well. There can be over a hundred personalities in one body, sone of which come and go and some of which develop later in life. I just hope that this film doesn't make people think that all people with this disorder are violent and kidnappers, although I do think the actor did a pretty great job depicting the disorder just from seeing the trailer.

text: Dear Sir/Madam, I am Mike Hunt, writing to tell you about my brilliant experience at Kingswood. I really enjoyed the activities at Kingswood. My favourite was the zip wire. When I got to the top of the 40 feet tower my knees were shaking, even though I knew I was totally safe because I was harnessed up and the instructors were qualified. The scariest part was when Johnny (the instructor) counted down from 3 to 1 and I walked off the edge of the tower and started zipping down at a whopping 25 miles per hour. My most scary activity was abseiling because the instructor kept telling you to lean back and you thought you were going to fall off. The food at Kingswood was absolutely delicious. On Sunday night we had a lovely roast with chicken, potatoes, Yorkshire pudding and to give it extra flavor we added nice, smooth gravy to it.  My favourite was the Spaghetti Bolognese because it is my most favourite food in the whole wide world The staff at Kingswood were funny and had a sense of humor. Johnny was really laid back and he even let the girls give him a hair makeover. Fishy Phil never gives up and really loves archery. Georgina was really girly and always played rubbish pop songs on Johnny‚Äôs portable speaker. Levon was really outgoing and due to her having dreadlocks she had never washed her hair in two years. The facilities at Kingswood were great. You can get up to a nice and warm power shower then go to your minty clean dorms to have a chat before going to activities. After a long day of activities you can go lie down on the super comfy mattresses and rest your head on the pillow and fall asleep. To get gifts or just get a drink you can go to shop and get your daily essentials for a super cheap price.      Overall my experience at Kingswood was amazing and I would definitely go again. Yours Faithfully, Mike Hunt

text: oh dear - my friend showed me this trailer the other day -  my guess is that these are ALL 23 of his personalities meeting each other for the first time. He has been sent to some hospital for experimental treatment where this new therapy helps him confront his splits so he can "release" them and find his "true" self...only something goes wrong and his personalities all want to fight to stay alive because they all think they are real. Some personalities are children, some male, some female, some teens, some helpers, some hurters. The beast is the twist - the beast could be the "therapist" who has split a normal man she kidnapped into 23 personalities - she may end up being his mom who also has split personalities! Or the beast could end up being the teenaged girl in the beginning - after all she is the one walking behind the other two laughing, oblivious girls, and she is the one who looks strangely at the man (is he their dad?) putting things in the trunk - right before she straps herself into the car - she seems to be the odd girl out. She probably hit him over the head with something and then put him in the trunk before hopping in as "the girl" and then the two in the back seat finally notice that he is not their dad. Or the girl could be an emerging new personality - a teenager - who is witnessing some of the other personalities. She will have to fight to earn her space with so many other personalities manifesting. Perhaps it's an inside look at how a person creates and absorbs multiple personalities. It looks interesting - and I found the part about changing the chemistry the most interesting. I think it's plausible that a person can change some aspects of themselves at will - the mind is a powerful computer - depending on how much control they have or don't have.

text: Hello friends, I have a message,  On Wednesday I got my work hours cut and now I can't support myself past this month. I'm having to give up my house and my car which I need for my 2 kids. I'm trying everything I can to save money but it's not going to be enough. Now I know I'm not going to make millions or even enough to cover my debt but if I don't start somewhere then I won't get anywhere. I made this channel years ago and I have always wanted to upload and live stream but I couldn't as my area has only just become available for fibre optic and I am getting my upgrade on the 18th of August. If you could please subscribe and watch my videos it would mean the world to me. To be given the opportunity to make enough to support myself is one thing, but to earn it is another. I promise I will do my utmost to deliver great quality content as often as possible to make you guys happy. Please support me. Livestream on 18/8/16, Thanks for taking the time to read this message. John.

text: Everything about this is disgusting. My wife has Dissociative Identity Disorder (previously referred to as Multiple Personality Disorder (NOT called split personalities)). DID is most often the result of severe childhood trauma -- people with DID are normally or have been victims. People with DID are constantly persecuted, shut away, harassed and mischaracterized. The reason they hide alters in public is not to protect you from them, but to protect themselves from your scorn and fear.  If someone has DID (a disorder that statistically affects more women) she is constantly putting all of her energy into appearing normal and leading a balanced and healthy life. Meanwhile she has to fight against the overwhelming image of fear that surrounds her disorder, specifically, all her life.Though DID is just as common as bipolar disorder, media treats it as an incurable malady that destroys everything around it.   My wife has worked hard to convince people that she is not crazy, psychotic, threatening, or going to harm them. This trailer made her terrified of how people will treat her all over again.  This. Is. Disgusting.

text: I am never going to watch an M. Night Shyamalan movie ever again after seeing this trailer. This is horribly offensive and dangerous. I feel like the film stereotypes people with mental illness to a dangerous degree with its implications that anyone who is bipolar can at any moment turn into a psycho murderer and a monster. I'm tired of the media portraying anyone with a mental illness as awful at worst, and useless at best. Especially men with mental illness. It's always the same; all men are portrayed as dangerous and needing to be put down, while all women are just unique and weird and only need to be cured by a great looking guy.

Both the mentally ill and the physically disabled are less likely to be violent towards others, both are considered disabled, yet ignorant and lazy creators like M Night portray the mentally ill as dangerous. You wouldn't portray a paraplegic as dangerous would you? People with learning disabilities? Blind people?  Please, instead of learning what mental illness is like from shit like this, actually look things up and learn from facts. Movies like this are part of the problem with how mental illness is portrayed.

text: This is such an infuriating, inaccurate representation of dissociative identity disorder. Once again, DID is being demonized and portrayed as terrifying and evil. I'm sick of this negative representation, when most people with DID are not aggressive. If they are, it's usually when provoked; like any other human being. Making almost every single media representation of DID so negative is completely disgusting, and it makes people with the disorder (in nearly every single case, abused people. DISSOCIATION IS CAUSED BY TRAUMA) afraid to have their disorder, when in reality it is a part of them! This depiction of DID is completely disrespectful to people who actually have it.

text: On one hand: James McAvoy is a great actor, and can play his roll to awesome extents. Also, the Concept of the movie is brilliant; 3 girls abducted by a man with MPD (or just really frick frackin clever) ¬†and it's up to the girls to try and get out with the help of one of the man's many personalities that could possibly hurt or help them.¬† Really a splendid set up for a suspense/ thriller¬†movie.   On the otherhand: it's an M. Night Shyamalan film, which honestly set's it up for a downfall in someway. Shyamalan is Infamous and Notorious for throwing in unnecessary and overly bad twists (In my opinion) and or ends up throwing in something supernatural to throw the plot along. He's also been known to give the characters really bland personalities, rendering his movies predictable. Laughable. or a combination of the two.   SO case in point of my opinion: I'm interested, but i'm not going to get overly hyped about solely because it IS a Shyamalan movie. so meh, just gonna have to wait till it comes out to see it.

text: um... not all mentally ill people are violent. i have bipolar disorder (that was professionally diagnosed!) and i'm not violent at all. i hate seeing mentally ill people always portrayed as this super unstable violent yandere type. like, yeah, there are cases where some mentally ill people are violent towards others but it's not common.  just think about it this way. if someone tells you they're in a wheelchair, usually you don't presume they're super violent and unstable. but if someone is mentally ill, some people would assume the person is going to lash out at them. what if this movie was about a cancer patient who kidnapped and tortured people? the media would attack it very quickly because cancer is a serious illness that should'nt be put in more of a negative light that it's already in. treat mental illnesses like physical illnesses, because they're equally as intense and life-ruining. sorry for the terrible grammar. i wrote this in a rush.

text: This movie makes me incredibly upset because I have bipolar disorder and autism, and actively spend every single second of my life trying to disprove the idea that mentally ill people are violent/evil. And knowing people are going to watch this and get entertainment out of it, out of an actual disability that people have, makes me want to lock myself inside my wardrobe (which I often do when I am upset). Please don't go see this movie. Please don't support the demonetization of mentally ill/neurodivergent/disabled people.

text: Now we ponder why specifically this guy targeted the lead girl. First of all this man with split personality disorder is actually the girl's true father. She was adopted during a young age and now he is returning to get her back for the special occasion. The plot twist comes when she found out this truth and she had to make a choice in deciding who is the real father. The pressure is on because she have to decide when her adopted father shows up at this 23 identities man's place and she have to kill one. The kicker is that she decided to kill the adopted father because she felt a father-daughter relationship with one of the personalities and decided that it was worth living with The Beast.

text: Can you say "stigma" anyone?? Movies like this are incredibly damaging to people who suffer from mental illness. The media portrays them this way so much that people start to believe the mentally ill should be feared. It's simply not true. They aren't maniacal killers, so stop portraying them that way. In fact, the disabled and mentally ill are more likely to be victims than any other population. Stop fear-mongering and dehumanizing the mentally ill for the sake of entertaining the ignorant.

text: I like how everyone is deeming this movie as a distress to DID when in all fairness, it is simply just a movie and does not illustrate any individual persons, groups or things parted with this disorder. DID is something that exist and everyone's system are different so I'm sure someone had a few similarities with this man and no not as in abducting a few kids. My advice if you wish to see this film, come with a mature mind. Don't assume the people behind this are all jackasses because they gave the character DID and you may have had it and none of what going on has ever occurred (to your knowledge that is). Some mental disorders can lead to behaviour such as shown in SPLIT and people may actually believe EVERYONE with DID will kidnap children and go psycho. My motto is we are not crazy. The ideal human behaviour is civilised meaning that our government says which traits(brain development)are considered as normal(based on the majority). Seeing one who is not considered are feared which is a crazy way to do things. We are all different. Disorders are differences and they're not so different because no victim is special. I can stand saying I have bipolar and when I look to my right, someone is saying just the same beside me. We need to laugh at reality(the reality to the unknown minority). That's why we have comedians. Stop getting "butt hurt". Come maturely is all i ask.

text: Dear people with D.I.D:  Please don't forget that this is a Hollywood movie and it's made for entertainment, not education. Hollywood makes many things look bad which is why instead of boycotting, educate people because lets face it, no matter how much you boycott, it's still going to be released and billions of people are still going to see it. This movie doesn't define you. You define yourselves, so create a definition.  If you lose friends because of your disorder, as much as it hurts, remember that they dont deserve you. Not only would they  have you as a friend, but your alters as well. Plus, if you really lose them because they find out you have DID, they're not really your friends, now are they? You don't need that kind of negativity in your life. You deserve to be surrounded by people who love you for the beautiful person you are üòò  I will say though, if you have littles, please treat them like any other child and protect them. Dont necessarily do your best to keep the movie from them but also dont tell them about it. If they find out about it and they get upset, console them and let them know that that is not who you are and that this movie will not change how people look at you. Try to keep them their happy selves.   Remember, dont hate, but educate. That is the best way to deal with things like this ‚ù§   Love and light, Abigail üòò  P.S. if anyone would like to vent, feel free to message me. I myself do not have this disorder but I am always here to help and listen ‚ù§
author: Valerie Carter

text: I am disappointed. I am sure the movie hits all the right notes in terms of scaring and startling you and is well-acted.  The problem is that the movie portrays someone with a disease of the brain (dissociative identity disorder-DID) who is therefore violent and frightening because of his disease.  The indirect message: people who have DID are dangerous, violent, threatening, etc.  That is a cruel, false message that can negatively impact perceptions of people with DID.  It's almost cliche to say mental illness is stigmatized.  I thought Hollywood would have gotten the message by now.    Obviously, a responsible approach would be a movie that depicts a character with DID and its impact of his/her life, etc. It would be true-to-life and shed light.  A truly interesting movie, similar to "A Beautiful Mind" starring Russel Crowe. That movie gave audiences the opportunity to see what it was like to live with his mental illness.  With "Split" we get the horror movie treatment.  Some may think I am "too sensitive."  I don't like when an innocent group of people are stigmatized as dangerous.  That makes me just the right amount of sensitive.  What do YOU think?
author: Casey R

text: It really angers me that people are saying that this movie puts mentally ill people in a bad light. First of all, every person is different even WITH a psychological illness. It is always wrong to assume that every one person who suffers is the same as the next. There is no way that mentioning one mentally ill individually can offend every person who suffers, everyone is different and cannot be compared for better or worse. Second of all this is a FICTIONAL horror movie. Although it is based on mental illness, it is not an educational documentary. The character suffers with a real disorder, but he is fictional and it is over exaggerated to tell an interesting story with a gripping twist. It is not made to educate us about the reality of illnesses, just to entertain us. If you want to learn about the reality of mental illnesses I suggest research, reading, and possibly taking courses to learn about it. Like I said this movie is just aiming to entertain us, not say; "This is how mentally ill people behave" that would be wrong and offensive.  There are many people in my life who I love who suffer with a mental illness. Two of them suffer with MPD/DID and I know that they would find this movie interesting, and gripping as a horror MOVIE. They know for sure that their illness is nothing like that, and that this movie is not trying to make people understand how the illness actually is.   If this movie really IS trying to say something about mental illnesses, I think it is trying to see that people gain empathy. As I was watching this I felt fear for the girls, but I wanted the main character who suffers to get help. It made sense to me why he suffered, due to the awful upbringing he didn't deserve. Although dangerous, he deserved help, care and to live a peaceful life, which he sadly couldn't have.   Watch the movie, enjoy that it is a fantasy. Do not see this as an educational video on mental illnesses, because it isn't AT ALL a representation of how they actually are.

text: I never comment on anything these days, but I need to sign in for this.This film has the most astounding endings I have ever seen ever in any movie, ever, but it is truely rewarding if you have watched previous Shyamalan films especially at the time of the release. When sitting through this towards the end I thought this was a pretty good film, solid entertainment ide say, the scene Kevin talks to the mirror I hear the unbreakable theme, I actually thought to myself, "its a great theme-bit cheap to re-use it from a film thats 15 years old" then the scene in the diner, i hear the news report, I involuntarily start to sweat as the music gets louder my heart starts to race I was slowly figuring out what I was seeing I then see bruce willis and he mentions " mr glass" I was stunned. I actually couldnt control my sweating it was so awesome, no film had ever made me feel that way before I definitely didnt see that coming. Absolute genius film making.

text: Spoiler alert don't read. The movie was pretty good with the best part about it being the acting of mcavoy. The predicable parts were the two girls that died who were pretty obviously expendable from the beginning. The dr was also an interesting actress, but failed to say the 3 magic words she wrote down to save her own life, and instead left it for the unbeknownst girls later in the scene who would somehow understand that reading the full name out loud would bring the alter up without knowing. I appreciated the suggestion of violence rather than seeing the actual violence not bc it maintained sympathy for the character but bc it spared us the goreporn in so many movies. But it did spare us the horror. I wish the movie had relied more on the supernatural but not much more, and the plot sort of fell apart at the demented scene where he deems her "pure" bc he sees her scars. Also the element of the story of her maintaining quiet for the incestuous relationship with her uncle is not completely plausible, nor particularly satisfactory as she goes home to more twisted horror. Despite saving herself from certain death.

text: Mr. Shamalamadingdong comes up with some weird/dumb shit but this movie is a total hit. James McAvoy is a genius in the antagonist role for this movie. Although I'm not sure I'd say that his adult/human personalities are quite as believable as Tatiana Maslany when she plays her different roles in orphan black but it was still a psychologically engaging movie and I thoroughly enjoyed it. The part I enjoyed most about the movie however was the message given off by the main protagonist. Spoiler alert: She is the kind of girl that would get bullied but when the other girls actually get to know her, it turns out that she's the most gifted out of all of them and her lone survival demonstrates that in multiple ways.

text: I can appreciate how talented James McAvoy is, in fact, I'm a huge fan myself. But I have a really bad impression of this movie, even if it is a FICTION masterpiece.  My brother has D.I.D., and I find this movie a non-accurate representation of these people in the media. It is inappropiate to showcase a mental condition, as harmless as D.I.D, in such a violent and terrifying way. D.I.D is a mental condition, that if it is not well understood, you are going to get carried away by all these misrepresentations in the media. D.I.D. is NOT dangerous, people with this disorder suffer from misunderstandings around them thanks to society. People that suffer from this condition are usually victims of a traumatic event as children, and the alters are generated by the brain as a mechanism of protection to the child. Alters are very unlikely to hurt anyone, they are, like us, other human beings with hopes of normal lives. Ps: This comment is in no way intended to spread hatred to the actors, nor the studio. It is just my personal opinion in regards to the portrayal of the character with D.I.D. I hope this was at the very least informative, and helped clear some things up. Thanks for reading Have a great day!

text: As someone actually diagnosed with DID. This is very offensive. I recently was diagnosed and I had no idea I had DID. I didn‚Äôt know much about it but all I knew was how the media portrayed it. So of course I thought I was a monster. I was absolutely terrified, because of films like this. I would never tell anyone that I have DID because after this film I would be looked at like someone who isn‚Äôt capable of living a normal life, and a monster. Which is not true whatsoever. Most cases of DID are not even half as bad as this movie portrays it to be. I don‚Äôt mean to be a bitch, and bash of Shyamalans films . I am just hurt and offended. I know their is nothing to be done it‚Äôs all ready come out. But I just hope everyone is well informed on what DID is actually like. I live a normal life, I am 18 in high school, straight A student, I have a boyfriend, a big family. I am normal I act normal. I am capable and stable. I have never been violent ever. I hope that no one has to feel the way I felt after been diagnosed and watching this. It‚Äôs absolutely disgusting and wrong and hurtful. If you are like me and have DID you are not a monster, you are capable of living a normal life. Don‚Äôt be scared to get help.

text: Okay, just letting you all know that people with DID are 100% NOT like this! Having DID does not make you dangerous or a criminal at all. Yes, some alters can be dangerous, but they have no more of chance to be than any other person.. Please please please know that the information in this film is not factually correct. I mean no harm to the people in this film, I just wanted to say that this film really hurt me and many people suffering with DID, and still continues to harm people with this disorder. It's also so painful to see people relate the disorder to this movie, because it is nothing like it. If you want factually correct information on this film there are some YouTubers and other people on social media that have videos you can watch, or you can research it if you would like to. Please everyone have a wonderful day/night/afternoon. Sorry for the long comment.
